President Donald Trump delivered a speech at Fort Myer in Arlington, Virginia, outlining his administration's new strategy for Afghanistan and South Asia. The President emphasized the need for an honorable and enduring outcome in Afghanistan and highlighted the threat of terrorism in the region. He emphasized that the United States will not announce specific dates for military actions and that conditions on the ground will guide the strategy. The President also called for a change in the approach towards Pakistan, urging the country to stop harboring terrorists. He expressed a desire to further develop strategic partnerships with India and asked NATO allies to contribute additional troops and funding. The President also emphasized the importance of supporting the Afghan government and military, while acknowledging that American military involvement in nation-building is over. He concluded by expressing his commitment to protecting American lives and interests and his belief that victory in Afghanistan is possible.